<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="307" pageId="5" pageNumber="304" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,612,636]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Description</emphasis>
(male, 
<typeStatus box="[317,413,612,636]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">holotype</typeStatus>
). Head black, frontal vitta blackish brown, matt, ochre near lunule; ocellar triangle brownish black and fronto-orbital plate blackish brown, shining, gena brown, antennal cavities blackish brown, shining, mouth margin yellow. Antenna brown, pedicel and scape pale ochre brown, palpi blackish brown. Thorax dark, scutum black shining, scutellum blackish brown. Postpronotal lobe and notopleuron ochre brown, anepisternum blackish brown, only narrowly bordered with yellow along upper and hind margin. Wing hyaline, with yellowish white base, veins ochre yellow. Calypters white, their margin and fringe yellowish white. Knob of halteres white, stem yellowish white basally. Legs brown, tibiae and tarsi pale, fore knees ochre yellow. Abdomen blackish brown, matt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[216,322,900,924]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,190,1520,1539]" captionTargetBox="[183,1092,226,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[172,1099,219,1512]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 1–6. 1–3 – Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov., J. 1 – wing; 2 – head in frontal view; 3 – the same in lateral view. 4–6 – A. macedonica sp. nov., J. 4 – head in frontal view; 5 – the same in lateral view; 6 – wing. Scales = 0.5 mm (Figs. 2–5) and 1 mm (Figs. 1, 6)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327824/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Figs. 2–3</figureCitation>
). Frons narrow, about as wide as 1.18 width of eye at level of anterior ocellus, slightly tapering toward lunule. Fronto-orbital plate little distinct, narrow, each about 0.17 width of frons, prominent beyond eye in profile, as broad as scape at level of lunule. Ocellar triangle large, anterior tip reaching level of ors setae. Two long ors setae and 2 shorter inclinate and slightly reclinate ori setae present, distance between the two ors twice as long as that between ori. Orbital setulae in one row, reclinate. Lunule low, only slightly higher than semicircular. First flagellomere covered with short hairs.Arista only 0.88 times as long as eye is high, short setulose. Eye higher than broad in relation 1.3: 1.0, totally bare. Parafacialia very narrow, gena highest in posterior part, reaching 0.28 height of eye. One stronger and long vi seta and 7–8 ge setae present. Epistoma lacking.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
Scutum with 0+3 dc setae, 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[443,453,1218,1233]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">st</superScript>
dc seta only 0.3 as long as 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[754,767,1218,1233]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">rd</superScript>
dc, 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[824,834,1218,1233]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">st</superScript>
dc seta inserted in front of sa setae line. Prescutellar seta as long as 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[578,588,1250,1265]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">st</superScript>
dc seta. Acrostichal setulae in 8–10 rows, some hairs reaching beyond line of 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[449,462,1282,1297]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">rd</superScript>
dc setae. One shorter ia seta and numerous presutural and postsutural ia setulae in 5–6 rows present, as long as acr setulae. Postpronotal lobe with 1 hu seta and 6–8 setulae. One long epa seta 1.5 times longer than 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[826,836,1346,1361]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">st</superScript>
dc seta. All usual setae present: 1 oc, 1 pvt, 1 vte, 1 vti, 1 ppl, 1+1 ntp, 1 mspl, 1 stpl, 1 sa, 1 prs, 1 bs, 1 as.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
Wing (
<figureCitation box="[215,276,1412,1436]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,190,1520,1539]" captionTargetBox="[183,1092,226,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[172,1099,219,1512]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs. 1–6. 1–3 – Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov., J. 1 – wing; 2 – head in frontal view; 3 – the same in lateral view. 4–6 – A. macedonica sp. nov., J. 4 – head in frontal view; 5 – the same in lateral view; 6 – wing. Scales = 0.5 mm (Figs. 2–5) and 1 mm (Figs. 1, 6)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327824/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) 2.52 mm long, costa reaching end of vein M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[758,766,1428,1443]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">1</subScript>
, wing apex in middle between R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[131,155,1460,1475]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">4+5</subScript>
and M 
<subScript attach="left" box="[231,239,1460,1475]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">1</subScript>
, relation of costal sections 2–4 as 3.64: 1.45: 1.00. Last section of CuA 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1014,1022,1460,1475]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">1</subScript>
short, only 0.75 as long as last but one section.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" box="[144,579,1508,1533]" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Legs: mid tibiae without strong pd setae.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,612,1596]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1127,219,1044]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="307" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">
Abdomen oval, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[331,343,1538,1553]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">th</superScript>
tergite as long as 5 
<superScript attach="left" box="[558,570,1538,1553]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">th</superScript>
tergite. Stridulating mechanism (
<figureCitation box="[929,1007,1540,1564]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) consisting of weakly sclerotized scales of same shape and size. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="307" pageId="5" pageNumber="304">Figs. 7–10, 12, 13</figureCitation>
): epandrium indistinctly broader than high in relation 1.25: 1.00. Surstylus (
<figureCitation box="[1004,1118,219,244]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="307">Figs. 9–10</figureCitation>
) with about 12 strong spines on inner surface. Cerci long, reaching 0.75 height of epandrium, clavate, with long setae. Phallus (
<figureCitation box="[505,606,283,308]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="307">Figs. 7–8</figureCitation>
) about 0.5 length of phallapodeme, symmetrical, distiphallus slightly pigmented, with short and narrow distal tubules. Mesophallus short, slightly broader than distiphallus. Hypandrium (
<figureCitation box="[667,744,347,372]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="307">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) V-shaped, with narrow but basally dilated arms. Ejaculatory apodeme (
<figureCitation box="[528,654,379,404]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="7.[113,152,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[145,1046,223,1484]" captionTargetId="figure-14@7.[136,1056,219,1506]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs. 7–14. Agromyza elladanensis sp. nov.,J. 7 – phallus in ventral view; 8 – the same in lateral view; 9 – surstylus ventral view; 10 – epandrium, surstylus and cercus in caudal view; 11 – stridulating mechanism; 12 – hypandrium; 13 – ejaculatory apodeme in lateral view; 14 – the same in dorsal view. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327826" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327826/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="307">Figs. 13–14</figureCitation>
) small, only 0.7 as long as phallus, V-shaped, 2.06 times as long as deep.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5327824" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5327824" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5327824/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="305" startId="6.[151,190,1520,1539]" targetBox="[183,1092,226,1493]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1128,1515,1593]" pageId="6" pageNumber="305">
Figs. 1–6. 1–3 – 
<taxonomicName authority="Černý, 2011" authorityName="Černý" authorityYear="2011" box="[292,490,1521,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Agromyza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="305" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elladanensis" status="sp. nov.">
